+### Retention Metadata
+
+Events also include a top-level `retentionMetadata` object so cleanup tools can
+make lifecycle decisions without inspecting raw payload contents. Producers should
+write these fields when the event is created, and readers should whitelist them
+before returning CLI/API/context output:
+
+```json
+{
+  "policyVersion": "lux.retention.v1",
+  "policyName": "project-jsonl-30d-or-10000",
+  "lifecycleState": "active",
+  "retentionDays": 30,
+  "maxEntries": 10000,
+  "expiresAtUtc": "2026-06-03T00:00:00.0000000Z",
+  "cleanupEligible": false,
+  "cleanupReason": ""
+}
+```
+
+Required retention metadata fields:
+
+- `policyVersion`: retention policy schema identifier used by the producer.
+- `policyName`: stable cleanup policy name, for example
+  `project-jsonl-30d-or-10000`.
+- `lifecycleState`: current event lifecycle, normally `active`; cleanup tooling
+  may later mark retained records as `eligible`, `compacted`, or `archived`.
+- `retentionDays`: age-based retention window for this event.
+- `maxEntries`: count-based retention cap for the project log.
+- `expiresAtUtc`: UTC timestamp when age-based cleanup may remove the event.
+- `cleanupEligible`: true only when cleanup may remove or compact the event.
+- `cleanupReason`: redacted human-readable reason when cleanup eligibility is
+  set by age, count cap, manual policy, or corruption recovery.
+
